  "prompt": "Dermatology: What are some best practices for treating bacterial scalp folliculitis?",
  "response": "Here are some best practices for treating bacterial scalp folliculitis:\n\n1. Medical Treatments:\n- Topical antibiotics (mupirocin)\n- Oral antibiotics (cephalexin, dicloxacillin)\n- Antiseptic shampoos containing chlorhexidine\n- Benzoyl peroxide wash\n- Prescription topical steroid creams for inflammation\n\n2. Hygiene Management:\n- Keep scalp clean and dry\n- Avoid sharing personal hair care items\n- Wash hair regularly with gentle, antibacterial shampoo\n- Change pillowcases frequently\n- Avoid tight hairstyles that cause friction\n\n3. Prevention Strategies:\n- Maintain good personal hygiene\n- Avoid excessive sweating\n- Use clean hair styling tools\n- Treat underlying skin conditions\n- Manage stress levels\n- Consider zinc or selenium sulfide supplements\n\n4. Additional Recommendations:\n- Avoid picking or scratching affected areas\n- Use breathable headwear\n- Apply warm compresses to reduce inflammation\n- Consider culture and sensitivity testing for persistent cases\n\n5. When to Seek Professional Help:\n- Severe or persistent symptoms\n- Signs of spreading infection\n- Fever\n- Significant pain or discomfort\n\nConsulting a dermatologist for personalized treatment is recommended.",
